Project two: Exploratory Analysis of Global Warming Tweets on January 2023.¶

This project is based on global warming tweets tweeted on January 2023. I have added emotion (anger, joy, opotimism and sadness) and gender at the end of each tweets. Emotion analysis was performed using a pre-trained model from Hugging Face (Twitter-roBERTa-base for Emotion Recognition). This is a roBERTa-base model trained on ~58M tweets and finetuned for emotion recognition with the TweetEval benchmark. Each tweet is classified into four emotions (joy, optimism, anger, and sadness) with a confidence score. In addition, gender was extracted based on first name of user account if a user account has a real first name and the gender can be identified by python package gender guesser.

Please develop an objective for your project based on your interest, develop 10 questions to support your objective, use both pyspark and SQL to answer each question and visualize your results. Summarize your findings at the end of the project. Discuss any patterns, trends, or insights you uncovered through your analysis. Reflect on how your findings relate to the original objective you developed.

Please check my attached research paper for possible analysis you can conduct. This paper won the best paper award in a recent conference of Northeast Decision Science Institute.

Objective:¶

Understand emotional reactions to global warming on Twitter during January 2023 in order to guide targeted communication strategies and further qualitative study.¶

Questions¶

In [8]:
from pyspark.sql import Window

# Creating an array of emotion scores with names
df = (df
    .withColumn(
        "emotion_array",
        F.array(
            F.struct(F.col("anger").alias("v"), F.lit("anger").alias("name")),
            F.struct(F.col("joy").alias("v"), F.lit("joy").alias("name")),
            F.struct(F.col("optimism").alias("v"), F.lit("optimism").alias("name")),
            F.struct(F.col("sadness").alias("v"), F.lit("sadness").alias("name"))
        )
    )
    # predicted emotion column (the emotion with highest confidence score)
    .withColumn("pred_emotion_struct", F.array_max("emotion_array"))
    .withColumn("pred_emotion", F.col("pred_emotion_struct.name"))
    .drop("emotion_array", "pred_emotion_struct")
)

# Extract date and hour from created_at for time analysis
df = df.withColumn("created_date", F.to_date("created_at")) \
       .withColumn("hour", F.hour("created_at"))

#PySpark
q4 = (df.groupBy("gender","pred_emotion")
       .agg(F.count("*").alias("count"))
     )

# compute totals per gender and percent
gender_totals = df.groupBy("gender").agg(F.count("*").alias("total"))
q4 = q4.join(gender_totals, on="gender")
q4 = q4.withColumn("pct", F.round(F.col("count")/F.col("total")*100,2)).orderBy("gender","pred_emotion")
q4_pd = q4.toPandas()

#SQL
sql = '''WITH t AS (
  SELECT gender, pred_emotion, COUNT(*) as count
  FROM df_t
  GROUP BY gender, pred_emotion
),
g AS (
  SELECT gender, COUNT(*) AS tot
  FROM df_t
  GROUP BY gender
)
SELECT t.gender, t.pred_emotion, t.count, ROUND(100.0 * t.count / g.tot, 2) AS pct
FROM t JOIN g ON t.gender = g.gender
ORDER BY t.gender, t.count DESC;'''
spark.sql(sql).show()

sql='''
WITH metrics AS (
  SELECT *, public_metrics.like_count AS like_count
  FROM df_t
)
SELECT pred_emotion, id, author, like_count, text
FROM (
  SELECT *, row_number() OVER (PARTITION BY pred_emotion ORDER BY like_count DESC) as rn
  FROM metrics
) t
WHERE rn <= 5
ORDER BY pred_emotion, like_count DESC;'''

df_engagement = df.select(
    "pred_emotion",

)

          F.avg("retweets").alias("avg_retweets"),
          F.avg("total_engagement").alias("avg_total_engagement")

#PySpark
keywords = ["climate","net zero","carbon","warming","policy","fossil"]

rows = []
for kw in keywords:
    sub = (df.filter(F.lower(F.col("text")).contains(kw))
             .groupBy("pred_emotion")
             .agg(F.count("*").alias("tweets"))

Summary/Reflection¶

The questions I designed show the distribution of emotions, how they vary across gender and time, which tweets gained the most engagement by emotion, and whether emotion signals are connected to tweet content, language, or authorship. Question 1 is simply the overview of the baseline emotion distribution for Jan 2023. The order by frequency is sadness, anger, optimism, then joy. Sadness makes sense to be the most prevalent emotions on the topic of climate change. Question 2 helps check whether a predicted_emotion is driven by strong confidence or small differences. The highest confidence was for anger, which was 32.5%, and lowest was joy at 13.6%. These confidence scores are not high, so the data is not wholly reliable, and we must bear that in mind when performing analysis. Question 3 shows daily emotion trends, and we see a large spike of both sadness and optimism on January 13. I found this article released this day: https://climateandeconomy.com/2023/01/13/13th-jan-2023-todays-round-up-of-climate-news/. The article contains a lot of negative climate news. Question 3 also shows that joy is the least variable. Question 4 is interesting because it shows that women are more optimistic about climate change while men are more angry. Question 5 shows time-of-day patterns, which is relatively stable based on the quantity of tweets. There are few joyful tweets at any point, but the other three emotions rise in the daytime. Question 6 shows which tweets gain the most likes by emotion, and it uncovers that though there are a decent amount of optimistic tweets, they get even fewer likes than ones classified as joy. We also see that a few authors show patterns of emotion in their tweets. Similarly, question 7 shows average engagement by emotion, where anger is surprisingly the lowest average engagement. Question 8 depicts engagement differences by gender and emotion, which signals that men get many more likes than women on average. Women get the most engagement on joyful tweets while men get most on anger. To clarify where these emotions are directed, I examined keywords in question 9 that prompt specific emotions. The most anger is directed at net zero and policy, which leads me to suspect that some of those people are against preventative measures for climate change due to the widespread insistence of some American politicians that climate change is a hoax, as these keywords should theoretically have high optimism scores. "Carbon", "climate", and "warming" all have high sadness scores, which is to be expected, but there is a surprising amount of optimism for "fossil" and "carbon", too. Finally, question 10 finds authors who disproportionately post angry content, which is good for network analysis like bot/influencer checking. The user "emojizedcom" posts much more angry content than any other user, doubling the second most frequent.

My objective for this project was to understand emotional reactions to global warming on Twitter during January 2023 in order to guide targeted communication strategies and further qualitative study. The ten research questions successfully established a baseline emotional distribution, identified key demographic and content drivers, and highlighted areas of data uncertainty that necessitate deeper qualitative exploration. Sadness is the most prevalent emotion, which aligns with the serious nature of climate change and suggests a need for communication that acknowledges concern and grief. Anger and optimism are next, suggesting a polarized debate. Emotion is also highly reactive to external events, as shown by the spike in sadness and optimism on January 13th, coinciding with a day of negative climate news. To combat the association of anger with keywords like "net zero" and "policy", which is counter-intuitive for climate advocacy, communications should be designed to either counter these anti-policy arguments or to shift the angry discussion toward constructive, solution-based policy.
